{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oedipusrex_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280607733/1957081901/0334.xml":{"full_text":"A-22\nTHE EVENING STAR. Washington. D. C.\nMONO AT. AUGUST IS.\n\"\u2022\"Business\nFall Business Outlook\nBright, NICB Reports\nBy WILLIAM A. MILLEN\nThe National Industrial Conference Board said today busi\nness this fall looks Rood.\nIt based this statement on a poll of industrial concerns\non the business outlook. The board said the majority art\noptimistic regardin\u00df prospective new orders and dollar billings.\nIt declared many are planning to boost their rates of produc-\ntion and look forward to im\nps ovement in before-tax profits\ndi-ring the balance of the year.\n\u2018Manufacturers of electrical\nIn iustrial equipment, hard\nware. general industrial ma\nchinery instruments, controls\nar d apparatus, nonferrous met\nalei and office equipment are\nparticularly cheerful,\u201d said the\nbuard. \u201cProducers of apparel\nand related products, construe- j\ntion materials, paper and allied\nproducts also see a bright sec\nond half.\u201d\nBut the board\u2019s canvass\nshowed some soft spots. The\nweakness in steel production is\nbalanced by full employment, a\nhigh level of buying power and\nsustained consumption, a pe\ntroleum executive pointed out.\nThe most troublesome prob-;\nlem cited by a number of com\npanies surveyed was the squeeze\non profit margins. Several\nfirms reported price cutting is,\non the increase due to keen\ncompetition. Overproduction is\nfeared by some and the tight\nmoney situation worries several\ncompany executives, they ad\nvised the board. Expansion\nand modernization programs 1\ncontinue as capital expendi-\ntures move ahead, the board\neaid.\ni\nSouthern Pacific Head i\nTo Get Transport Award\nWhen the National Defense\nTra n s p ortation Association\nmeets here at the Sharaton- 1\nPark Hotel November 21, the\npresident of the Southern Pa\ncific Railroad Co., Donald J.\nRussell, will be specially hon\nored.\nThis was announced today by\nthe Defense Department, which\nsaid the formal presentation of 1\nthe eighth annual award will\nbe made to Mr. Russell at the\nassociation's annual dinner. It\nwill be bestowed on \"the person\nwho has made the most out-\nstanding contribution in the\npreceding year to the solution\nof emergency transportation\nproblems affecting national de- i\nsense.\u201d\nThe Joint Transportation\nCommittee of the Joint Chiefs\nof Staff selected the winner of\nthe award. The Defense De\npartment said Mr. Russell has\ndevoted his entire career to the\njp*'\nWINGS WHEELS\n\u2022y CHARLES YARIROUGH\nWithout the fumbling which\nhas marked the lack of pro\ngress in getting Washington a\nsecond airport. Montgomery\ncounty is moving one toward\nreality.\nAdmittedly 10 years behind\nthe aviation times, the Mary\nland neighbor now has the au\nthority. most of the money and\nthe well-oiled machienry to put\nthe project over. Even the\nblessings of the Civil Areo\nnautirs Administration are\navailable.\nCurrently under study by the\ncounty's new five-man Au\nthority is the economic aspect.\nDoes it have the potential of\npaying for itself?\nThe answer may be out by\nlate October.\nTo the Montgomery County\nAirport Committee there Is no\ndoubt about the answer. Last\nweek, the Committee had an\nother\u2014and probably one of Its\nbest\u2014talking points. A small,\naviation-related industry ex\npressed interest in investing\nabout $1 million in a site ad\njoining an aircraft landing\natrip in the lower county.\nThe Washington area, once\nringed with more than 10 fly\ning fields, is down to a hand\nful and Montgomery County's\nonly one Congressiona 1\u2014 is\nbarely operating. Real estate\nmoney shines brighter than\naircraft parking fees and main\ntenance dollars to most oper\nators. Soon the little bird is\ngoing to be without a nest.\nMontgomery County has\n$275,000 in Federal airport\nfunds available for matching.\nThe Council has appropriated\nanother $250,000. If the Au\nthority comes up w Ith an\naffirmative answer this fall and\nthe Council approves the sale\nof airport bonds, there'll be a\nnew nest across the District\nline.\n\nOidsmobile, oldest auto man\nufacturer in the Nation, be-1\ncomes 60 years old Wednesday\nend those nearest and dearest\nto the occnsion dusted off a bit\ncf doggerel to emphasize the\ndeparture from one horse to\nplus 275.\n\"It doesn't shy at papers as\nthey blow along the street;\n\"It cuts no silly capers on\nthe dashboard with its feet;\n\"It doesn't paw the sod up\nall around the hitching post;\nIt doesn't scare at shadows\nas a man would at a ghost;\n\"It doesn't gnaw the manger\nand it doesn't waste the hay:\n\"Nor put you into danger\nwhen the brass bands play.\u201d\n\nNext year is the one in which\nthe auto manufacturers have\nagreed to tone down claims on\nperformance, acceleration and\nhorsepower, even though most\nevery new model will have more\npower.\nft m\nDONALD J. RLSSKLL\nexpansion and improvement of\nAmerican railroads for com\nmerce and defense. He began\nwork with the railroad as time\nkeeper for a maintenance of\nway gang in 1920.\nAmong his contributions, the\ndepartment cited Mr. Russell\u2019s\ndevelopment of a common al\nternate railroad route around\nthe congested city of Los An- 1\ngeles; his work in clearing\nearthquake damaged railroad\ntunnels when rail service on\nthe San Joaquin route in Cali\nfornia was interrupted and the\npresent building of a rock\ncauseway across Great Salt\nLake, scheduled for completion\nin 1960. to allow full-speed op\neration of trains across the\nlake. He is a member of the\nBusiness Advisory Council of\nthe Commerce Department and\na director of the Association of\nAmerican Railroads.\nThe theme of this year\u2019s con\nvention and transportation\nforum of the association to be\nheld here is \u201cThe Shape of\nThings to Come in Tr ansporta\ntion and Logistics.\u201d\nMore than 60 distinguished\nGovernment, military and ci\nvilian transportation leader*\nwill appear before the conven\ntion at various meetings and\nforums, officials said. These in\nclude: Director of Defense Mo\nbilization Gordon Gray, Gen\neral Services Administrator\nOne which won't hurt a bit\nfrom ithe de-emphasis will be\nthe fuel injection competition\nChevrolet Corvette. All the\nsalesman will have to do is to\ninvite a prospect to drive it.\nThe rest is obvious. Chevrolet\u2019s\nBaltimore office brought one of\nthe little red beasts over last\nweek and it performed like a\nwilling thoroughbred, but it is\nsomething which should be\nhandled with caution for the\nfirst 500 miles. It is no play\nthing and if the driver isn\u2019t\nwith it at all times, he'll find\nhimself back there.\n\nTrans World Airlines puts its\nnew Jetstream Starllner, the\ncountry's largest commerce 1\nliner, into service betwee*\nWashington and San Francisco\nThursday. It will be daily and\nnon-stop; first class and tour\nist. Jetstream service between\nNational airport and Los An\ngeles begins September 15.\nThe plane, a modified Lock\nheed Constellation, has a\nwingspread of 150 feet, but has\nbeen lightened to permit higher\nspeed over longer range. In\naddition to other innovations,\nthe engines have been posi\ntioned further from the fuse\nlage to trim interior noise\nlevels to a claimed 23 per cent\nunder contemporary aircraft.\n\nJohn Pusey's Allied Motor*\nat 1100 Sixth street N.W., ex\npects the first of the new\nGerman Lloyd 600 Alexander*\nin next week, with new 4-speed\ntransmission, roll-up windows\nj and other refinements.\nReal S. A. Transposes Aereos\nof Brazil, subsidiary of Cali\nfornia Eastern, will convert it*\nConvalrs to turbo-prop engine*.\nThe new issue of Fortune\ni Magazine is telling how Ford\nrecruited Its new Edsel dealer*\nfrom the ranks of General\nMotors and Chrysler. North\nAmerican Aviation 1* planning\na 500-mtle-an-hour utility Jet\nat company expense as an\nanswer to military require\nm\u00bbnts with engine* well aft\nlike the French Caravelle.\nDr. Albert Fogg, director of\nBritish Motor Industry Re\nsearch is over here, telling of\nresearch which he say* will\ni cut the fuel consumption of\nBritish cars up to 30 per cent,\ni Myrle St. Auhin, of the\nAutomobile Manufacturers' As\nsociation service managers\ncommittee, says the auto me\nchanics ranks will need 40,000\nnew recruits annually for the\nnext 18 years to keep pace,\ni the Flying Tigers line re\nports that a new fleet of Lock\ni herd Super II Constellations\nI has enabled the carrier to\nshow it* first monthly operat\ni ing profit since September of\ni last year.\nllt&r A\nOLDSMOBILE Bl\u00dfTHDAY\u2014Oldsmobile, to show what 60 years in the\nauto business can do, wheeled out a 1905 model and put it alongside\nthe new F-88 experimental sports car. The oldest suio-making firm\nin the country, Oldsmobile is 60 on Wednesday.\nFranklin Floete, Chairman\niOwen Clarke of the Interstate\nCommerce Commission, Civil\nAeronautics Administrator\nJames T. Pyle, Chairman Clar\nence C. Morse of the Federal\nMartitime Board. Admiral Ar\nleight A. Burke, Chief of Naval\nOperations: Gen. Maxwell D.\nTaylor, Army Chief of Staff,\nand Lt. Gen. C. S. Irvine, Dep\nuty Chief of Staff for Materiel\nof the Air Force.\nMaryland C. Schedule\nManagement Parley\nAnnouncement was made\ntoday that the ninth annual\nOffice Management Confer\nence will be held October 24-\n:26 at the University of Mary\nland. College Park. Md.\nArthur S. Patrick professor\nof office management, will be\nthis year\u2019s general chairman.\n1 4 Door R'visro\niy-i* T\",7n,i..' I\nfa?\nS-T-R-E-T-C-H-E-D OUT TERMS I .whuant NtwviJgff\nlm is*, l -rssft* yIM\n*Ntw Advanced Variabl* Pitch Dynaflow It tho only Dynollow Buick buildt today.\nIt It ttondord an Roodmaster, Suptr ond Ctntury aptional 4J modott \u2022xfro\ngg g YOUR AUTHORIZED BUICK DEALER COlf Sp C al Sof9,y\u00dfuzr\u00a7r tlandard on optional othar Sorlis\ni The conference is sponsored by\nthe university's Department of\nOffice Techniques and Manage\nment of the College of Business\n1 and Public Administration in\nco-operation with various chap\nters of the National Office\nManagement Association in\nthis region.\n1\nD. C. Banking Group\nSet for Atlanta Meeting\nA large delegation of Wash\ningtonians is expected to at\ntend- the 33d annual conven\nl tion of the National Associa\ntion of Bank Auditors and Con\ntrollers to be held in Atlanta\nOctober 7-10.\nRobert E. Kendrick, jr.. con\ntroller of the Bank of Com\nmerce here and chairman of\nthe Auditors\u2019 Section of the\nDistrict Bankers Association,\nsaid today \u201ca lot of Interest has\nbeen expressed here in the\ni forthcoming convention.\u201d He\ni said the list of those planning\nto attend is now being compiled.\nThe association's president,\ni Steve H. Bomar, estimates that\n1,400 to 1.600 people will at\ntend the four-day convention,\nifrom all part of the Nation.\nSenator Talmadge, Democrat\nof Georgia, wil be among the\ntop speakers, who Include:\nJoseph C. Welman, incoming\npresident of the American\nBankers Association. The au\nditors\u2019 association, which con\nducts research and educational\nprograms to improve bank au\nditing and control procedures,\nwill sponsor a series of meet\nings devoted to various topics\nat the convention.\nNEXT SUMMER j\nwe\u2019re going ft\nto Europe\nNo more dull vacations that we\ncan just \u201cafford.\" We're doing jufi\nwhat a lot of our friends have Jl/\\ 'V\ndone. We've opened a share \"l\\ Vr r \\j 'b, L\\\nsavings account at Equitable .T-q -wf|| '.P\nand are saving regularly toward J, IJ I\na REAL trip next year. V\u2014/ '**l mjM\nThe big compound dividends f If\nthey pay will help a lot. And\nour money is insured up to V\nSave now for the trip of your dreams -tri\n(fp Equitable Savings and Loan Association\n#915 F STREET N.W. NAtional 8-1741\nEdward L. McAleer, President\nWHEATON ORANCH\u2014II433 GEORGIA AVE. LOckwood 4-0001","height":"28719","width":"18244"